02:24.667 --> 02:30.667
<i>In 1931, the Russian film director
Sergei Eisenstein</i>

02:30.876 --> 02:33.417
<i>travelled to Mexico to make a film.</i>

02:33.917 --> 02:38.626
<i>It was tentatively to be called</i>
iQue viva Mexico!

02:39.667 --> 02:42.542
<i>Eisenstein had a worldwide fame</i>

02:42.626 --> 02:46.626
<i>based on the reputation of only three films,</i>

02:46.709 --> 02:48.917
<i>all made in Soviet Russia.</i>

02:50.584 --> 02:54.709
Strike, <i>a violent tale of civilian unrest</i>

02:54.834 --> 02:57.084
<i>viciously crushed by authority,</i>

02:58.584 --> 03:01.417
The Battleship Potemkin,<i> a violent account</i>

03:01.501 --> 03:04.876
<i>of a naval mutiny over rotten meat,</i>

03:05.917 --> 03:08.751
<i>and</i> October, <i>a violent celebration</i>

03:08.834 --> 03:10.709
<i>of the Russian Revolution.</i>

03:12.626 --> 03:15.209
<i>In the West, the film</i> October

03:15.292 --> 03:18.001
<i>was called</i> Ten Days That Shook The World.

03:19.501 --> 03:21.626
<i>This present film might be called</i>

03:21.709 --> 03:25.126
Ten Days That Shook Eisenstein.

04:15.292 --> 04:17.541
I arrive accompanied by flies.

04:17.625 --> 04:20.584
They have been with me ever since
I crossed the Mexican border.

04:20.666 --> 04:22.167
I brought them with me from Moscow.

04:32.751 --> 04:33.751
I recognise them.

04:34.209 --> 04:37.751
They are Soviet flies, spy flies...
Russian accents,

04:37.834 --> 04:40.626
a growling, gruff, ill-mannered buzz.

04:40.751 --> 04:42.334
They have bloodshot eyes, like me.

04:42.417 --> 04:44.209
Do I have bloodshot eyes?
Do I have bloodshot eyes?

04:44.292 --> 04:46.001
Do I have bloodshot eyes?
Do I have bloodshot eyes?

04:46.084 --> 04:48.001
Of too much looking. Too much...

04:48.084 --> 04:49.626
<i>Too much looking.</i>

04:49.709 --> 04:53.209
- Diego.
- Sergei, my friend!

04:53.834 --> 04:56.251
- You're welcome.
- <i>Grazie.</i>

04:56.792 --> 04:58.751
- Frida.
- Sergei.

04:59.834 --> 05:01.876
- <i>Bienvenido.</i>
- <i>Encantado.</i>

05:02.626 --> 05:05.126
Jorge Palomino Cañedo.
Your Guanajuato guide.

05:05.584 --> 05:06.959
Sergei Eisenstein.

05:07.042 --> 05:08.876
Sometimes a Russian film director

05:09.001 --> 05:11.084
or Russian film director retired.

05:12.751 --> 05:14.334
This is Aleksandrov.

05:14.417 --> 05:15.417
Always an actor.

05:17.292 --> 05:19.001
- Frida.
- Grisha.

05:19.084 --> 05:20.709
And this is Eduard Tisse, cameraman.

05:20.792 --> 05:22.209
The cameraman.

05:22.292 --> 05:23.292
- Frida.
- Tisse.

05:23.376 --> 05:24.584
Please take the suitcases.

05:25.584 --> 05:27.334
Welcome, ladies and gentlemen.

05:34.417 --> 05:35.459
Hey, look.

06:34.417 --> 06:36.376
Put all the red books over there.

06:36.459 --> 06:39.376
All the books with the blue markers
over there.

06:39.459 --> 06:40.959
All English books by the bed.

06:42.626 --> 06:45.584
All American books under the bed.

07:17.626 --> 07:20.834
- Can I help?
- There is a trick, isn't there?

07:20.917 --> 07:22.376
What am I doing wrong?

07:22.459 --> 07:23.501
I expect nothing.

07:24.709 --> 07:27.167
We don't have showers in Moscow.

07:27.251 --> 07:28.959
In fact, we don't have showers in Russia.

07:29.709 --> 07:31.917
Baths, Turkish baths.

07:32.042 --> 07:34.001
And wash basins.

07:34.084 --> 07:37.459
Sometimes we have running water.
Sometimes we have water.

07:37.542 --> 07:39.626
Sometimes we have just the empty taps.

07:39.709 --> 07:42.042
Sometimes we have
to break the ice in the tank.

07:42.126 --> 07:43.126
Often...

07:43.917 --> 07:45.459
We don't wash.

07:58.317 --> 08:00.167
What are you laughing about?

08:00.251 --> 08:02.292
A Russian body. Very white.

08:02.376 --> 08:04.709
We rarely see the Sun in Moscow,

08:04.792 --> 08:07.292
and we never undress in public.

08:07.376 --> 08:09.751
- Then I can't be public.
- Public enough.

08:12.417 --> 08:13.626
That's his.

08:13.709 --> 08:16.209
And a very well-fed body.
Pea-soup, pickled cabbage,

08:16.292 --> 08:18.126
salty bacon, sour milk, turnips?

08:19.334 --> 08:20.376
When we can get it.

08:24.084 --> 08:25.751
See you at breakfast?

08:25.834 --> 08:29.042
Tortillas, tamales, chicken burritos,

08:29.126 --> 08:33.833
chimichangas, sopecitos,
huarachitos, pan de muerto...

08:33.917 --> 08:36.333
Hey! Warm water?

08:37.833 --> 08:39.208
Being naked in public?

08:40.167 --> 08:42.583
Or a response to an amiable young man?

08:44.167 --> 08:45.709
Signor Prick, behave!

08:46.584 --> 08:49.334
He's handsome, it's true.

08:50.417 --> 08:52.709
And he's seen you, it's true.

08:52.792 --> 08:57.042
But you are a foreigner
with a Russian passport,

08:57.126 --> 08:58.667
a limited visitor's visa,

08:58.751 --> 09:00.917
and very little sexual experience.

09:01.001 --> 09:02.667
You would be woefully disadvantaged.

09:03.501 --> 09:05.959
Besides, you are here to make a film with me,

09:06.042 --> 09:08.834
and I need your frustrations
to feed my imagination.

09:09.501 --> 09:10.501
No dissipation.

09:11.126 --> 09:13.834
It leads to a dilution of energy.

09:16.084 --> 09:18.626
<i>I am a boxer</i>

09:19.084 --> 09:22.792
for the freedom of cinematic expression.

09:29.167 --> 09:31.417
I have never had my shoes shined for me.

09:31.501 --> 09:33.917
We don't do those sorts of things
any more in Soviet Russia.

09:34.959 --> 09:36.542
You're in México.

09:36.626 --> 09:38.042
Why don't you try it?

10:00.542 --> 10:02.834
I'm behaving like a colonial grandee.

10:03.251 --> 10:06.084
Shining shoes is tantamount to kissing feet.

10:06.167 --> 10:07.959
Who kisses feet any more?

10:08.042 --> 10:10.667
Do I tip him heavily
to cover up my bourgeois guilt?

10:10.751 --> 10:11.751
No.

10:11.834 --> 10:14.376
If you tip him, news of your generosity

10:14.459 --> 10:16.417
will be around the town in five minutes.

10:16.501 --> 10:19.167
And your shoes will never be yours again.

10:19.251 --> 10:21.084
They will be a host to fortune.

10:23.084 --> 10:25.834
You have come here for something other
than shiny shoes.

10:26.376 --> 10:27.376
What are you looking for?

10:29.834 --> 10:32.251
I came to Mexico to make a movie.

10:33.126 --> 10:35.126
I came to Mexico

10:35.209 --> 10:37.751
because my very first
theatre production in Moscow

10:37.834 --> 10:40.042
was called <i>The Mexican.</i>

10:40.126 --> 10:44.542
I came to Mexico because
you had a successful revolution

10:44.626 --> 10:45.876
five years before we did.

10:45.959 --> 10:47.584
I came to Guanajuato

10:47.667 --> 10:49.459
because you have here
a Museum Of The Dead.

10:49.542 --> 10:52.167
Maybe I have to make a film called
<i>Museum Of The Living.</i>

10:52.251 --> 10:55.167
Those are my excuses.
What are your excuses?

10:56.126 --> 10:58.751
I live here. I have a family here.

10:58.834 --> 11:01.251
I teach in Mexico City, and I teach here.

11:01.334 --> 11:02.542
And what do you teach?

11:02.626 --> 11:04.959
I studied as an anthropologist.

11:05.042 --> 11:08.001
And now I teach comparative religion.

11:09.626 --> 11:11.209
This is a Roman Catholic country.

11:11.751 --> 11:14.251
How come you are allowed
to talk about other religions?

11:17.292 --> 11:20.667
Roman Catholicism of México
is generous and all-embracing.

11:21.209 --> 11:22.334
Pantheistic.

11:22.417 --> 11:24.792
A bit of everything. Old and new.

11:24.876 --> 11:26.042
They just take what they need.

11:26.584 --> 11:29.667
<i>So much so, we should call it
Mexican Catholicism.</i>

11:30.459 --> 11:32.084
<i>They customised it.</i>

11:32.167 --> 11:33.792
<i>We have pre-Columbian equivalents</i>

11:33.876 --> 11:36.376
<i>for everything the Roman Catholics dreamed up.</i>

11:36.459 --> 11:40.126
<i>Certainly, we invented blood sacrifices
before you did.</i>

11:40.751 --> 11:44.084
<i>Christianity adopted us.
We did not adopt Christianity.</i>

11:52.417 --> 11:54.959
It's Gideon. His name is Gideon.

11:57.251 --> 11:58.751
He was born blind.

11:58.834 --> 12:00.167
And the bells have made him deaf.

12:04.417 --> 12:05.709
There is a problem.

12:05.792 --> 12:07.209
They have been searching
through your books

12:07.292 --> 12:08.292
and found pornography.

12:10.167 --> 12:11.626
Are you a pornographer?

12:12.709 --> 12:14.001
I didn't think so up till now.

12:18.251 --> 12:20.001
One of the hotel maids arranging your books

12:20.084 --> 12:23.709
has taken some photographs,
but she is underage.

12:23.792 --> 12:26.584
Her mother found the photographs
and complained to the hotel.

12:26.667 --> 12:28.209
I am sure it can be sorted out.

12:28.667 --> 12:30.042
Stay in sight of your bodyguards.

14:34.459 --> 14:35.626
It's OK, boys.

14:38.376 --> 14:40.167
Sergei!

14:42.626 --> 14:44.459
Sergei!

14:55.834 --> 14:58.292
México!

14:58.376 --> 14:59.667
México!

15:05.501 --> 15:08.417
Guanajuato!

15:32.959 --> 15:34.959
Vomit and shit pour out of you in floods.

15:35.042 --> 15:36.126
I should not be here.

15:37.209 --> 15:39.334
I should be back in Russia,
being constipated.

15:39.417 --> 15:42.709
In Moscow, you can go for a week
without shitting once.

15:56.334 --> 15:58.751
Sergei? It's me. It's me, Cañedo. It's me.

16:04.417 --> 16:06.417
Come on. Let's go, let's go.

16:06.542 --> 16:08.867
It's just me, Cañedo.
Hey, it's OK.

16:11.334 --> 16:12.084
Come on.

16:17.709 --> 16:19.001
Stop it, stop it, stop it.

16:28.959 --> 16:30.709
Close your eyes, close your eyes.

16:34.417 --> 16:35.584
You know...

16:37.334 --> 16:40.501
You know, I sat like the Tsar

16:40.709 --> 16:43.876
on the throne of the Winter Palace.

16:45.584 --> 16:47.834
But the Tsar did not have running water.

16:48.251 --> 16:50.251
You Mexicans don't have tsars,

16:50.334 --> 16:52.167
but you do have running water.

16:53.501 --> 16:55.709
What is that noise?

16:55.792 --> 16:57.334
Someone banging on the pipes.

17:03.042 --> 17:04.126
Come on.

17:18.084 --> 17:19.709
OK. OK, hey.

17:20.084 --> 17:21.151
Wake up.

17:24.166 --> 17:25.376
Come on, come on.

17:32.542 --> 17:34.751
It's the 22nd of October.

17:35.501 --> 17:38.167
Someone is banging on the pipes

17:38.251 --> 17:42.709
to commemorate the start
of the Russian Revolution.

17:44.834 --> 17:48.501
No. It's the hotel plumber fixing the hot water.

17:48.751 --> 17:50.167
Go to sleep.

17:50.251 --> 17:52.876
The hot water of the Revolution.

17:54.167 --> 17:56.001
We shall all be cleansed

17:56.084 --> 18:00.209
with the hot water of the Revolution.

18:03.209 --> 18:04.334
Watch him carefully.

18:04.417 --> 18:06.792
Or you'll have Stalin on your backs.

18:06.876 --> 18:08.667
Stalin's reach is very long.

18:08.751 --> 18:10.751
If anything happens to him,

18:10.834 --> 18:13.042
you'll be picking ice
out of your asses in Siberia

18:13.126 --> 18:15.542
or have an ice-pick lodged in your brain!

18:32.959 --> 18:35.167
Here, your photographs.

18:35.876 --> 18:38.459
Put them away somewhere safe.

18:38.542 --> 18:41.042
Don't leave them lying around
for innocent chambermaids

18:41.126 --> 18:43.067
to steal and show to their mamás.

18:44.501 --> 18:46.042
But they are paintings.

18:47.042 --> 18:49.709
Mexican mothers
protecting their innocent daughters.

18:49.792 --> 18:52.042
We countered by accusing the maid
of stealing from guests.

18:52.626 --> 18:54.792
Is thievery worse than voyeurism?

18:55.876 --> 18:57.959
She should not be sacked for curiosity.

18:58.042 --> 18:59.584
You must get her reinstated.

19:01.042 --> 19:02.834
She's in the bar
with her mother and her father.

19:02.917 --> 19:04.751
- You could tell her yourself.
- No, you tell her.

19:04.834 --> 19:07.667
And tell her mother
her daughter's forgiven for stealing,

19:07.751 --> 19:09.709
and from now on, she's the only one

19:09.792 --> 19:11.626
to bring me my breakfast in bed
in the morning.

19:37.376 --> 19:40.542
The manager says it's a good job
she didn't take a look

19:40.626 --> 19:42.042
in your red suitcase.

19:42.126 --> 19:44.542
Oh? What's in the red suitcase?

19:44.626 --> 19:46.709
Enough to have you thrown in jail.

19:47.876 --> 19:50.626
And how did the manager

19:50.709 --> 19:52.792
know what was in the red suitcase?

19:53.876 --> 19:55.459
After the complaint, he searched everything.

19:56.667 --> 19:57.709
God, he has no right to do that.

19:57.792 --> 19:59.792
That's invasion of privacy!

20:00.676 --> 20:02.417
Look, he's winking at you.

20:03.376 --> 20:04.501
Curiously, it's a mark in your favour.

20:04.876 --> 20:07.417
But if you offend him,
he could use it against you.

20:08.084 --> 20:09.334
Tread carefully.

20:25.126 --> 20:26.959
The Camorristas.

20:27.042 --> 20:29.667
They are looking for
wealthy foreigners to prey on.

20:29.751 --> 20:31.501
They wait outside all the big hotels.

20:31.584 --> 20:34.501
And you are giving them
good reason to prey on you.

20:34.584 --> 20:36.376
That's why you have bodyguards.

20:39.792 --> 20:41.167
These are the small-time guys.

20:41.251 --> 20:43.001
We don't worry so much about them.

20:43.084 --> 20:46.126
They are posing as tough guys,
but they are lazy.

20:46.209 --> 20:48.167
The big guys are much tougher.

20:48.251 --> 20:50.959
And the real big guys, you'll never see.

20:52.251 --> 20:56.167
That's why you should try
and stop attracting attention.

20:56.251 --> 20:59.042
Don't get yourself photographed
and in the newspapers.

21:00.251 --> 21:02.292
If they smell a ransom possibility,

21:02.376 --> 21:04.751
they will be in and kidnap you.

21:04.834 --> 21:06.292
How much do you think you are worth?

21:07.709 --> 21:08.751
Not much.

21:10.667 --> 21:13.334
What will your government pay
to keep you alive?

21:13.417 --> 21:14.751
Nothing.

21:14.834 --> 21:18.167
Just trust that we are looking
after you properly.

21:18.251 --> 21:21.001
But maybe you are a Camorrista?

21:23.751 --> 21:27.376
If I am, then you are lost.

21:30.792 --> 21:32.126
You ought to make a film about them.

21:37.751 --> 21:39.667
The corpse at the door is wearing a red shirt,

21:39.751 --> 21:41.542
as you can see.

21:41.626 --> 21:45.001
Even among the dead,
the Camorristas have influence.

21:45.917 --> 21:48.334
Ransoming a corpse
is not uncommon in México.

23:36.376 --> 23:37.417
<i>Míralo.</i>

23:53.459 --> 23:55.876
Do you only have one suit?

23:55.959 --> 23:58.292
Well, I left Moscow with only $25.

23:58.376 --> 24:00.126
Russia has very little foreign currency,

24:00.209 --> 24:02.459
and that was all they could afford to give us.

24:02.542 --> 24:04.459
I get paid expenses here in Mexico.

24:04.542 --> 24:05.751
Or I get paid expenses,

24:05.834 --> 24:08.126
and I have to share with Tisse and Grisha.

24:09.251 --> 24:11.334
That suit is taking some punishment.

24:11.417 --> 24:13.001
You should buy yourself another.

24:13.084 --> 24:15.834
<i>It's my first American suit.
I bought it to walk down Sunset Boulevard</i>

24:15.917 --> 24:17.042
<i>with Charlie Chaplin.</i>

24:17.126 --> 24:20.001
<i>It's a sentimental matter.
I could not part with it.</i>

24:20.167 --> 24:23.167
This is my wife, Concepción.

24:26.667 --> 24:29.334
- This is Rolando.
- Good evening, sir.

24:29.417 --> 24:30.417
Good evening.

24:30.626 --> 24:32.584
The eldest was born
when I was studying troubadours

24:33.126 --> 24:36.667
and the second, Pascal,
when I reluctantly gave up God.

24:36.751 --> 24:39.167
Now I don't believe in God,
but I miss him,

24:39.251 --> 24:40.501
as did Pascal.

24:40.792 --> 24:43.501
I'm sorry. I have no Russian buttons.

24:43.584 --> 24:45.792
But these are curious.
What are they made of?

24:46.576 --> 24:47.792
Gun metal.

24:48.126 --> 24:51.626
They are stamped out
of discarded cartridge cases,

24:51.709 --> 24:53.167
pierced with two holes

24:53.251 --> 24:55.334
and glued to a piece of army blanket,

24:55.417 --> 24:57.501
which usually very quickly becomes unglued.

24:59.084 --> 25:00.876
A Russian soldier is told

25:00.959 --> 25:02.792
never to let his shoes out of his sight,

25:02.876 --> 25:04.084
if not out of his hand.

25:04.167 --> 25:07.459
Better still, always keep them on your feet.

25:07.542 --> 25:11.501
Shoes are the most precious item of clothing.

25:11.584 --> 25:14.126
Won't help your modesty,
scarcely keep you warm,

25:14.209 --> 25:18.376
but you will simply not be able
to function without shoes

25:18.459 --> 25:20.209
in any way at all.

25:23.417 --> 25:26.834
Don't worry. I'm a foreigner.
I'm a child abroad.

25:27.417 --> 25:29.667
Russia's so big
that nobody thinks about abroad.

25:29.751 --> 25:31.667
It's always too far away and well out of sight.

25:32.292 --> 25:33.792
We believe most of the time

25:33.876 --> 25:36.042
that "abroad" does not really exist.

25:36.126 --> 25:37.751
Does not really exist.
Does not really exist.

25:41.334 --> 25:43.792
I was earning money
from American publishers,

25:43.876 --> 25:46.292
<i>and I bought an old battered Ford car.</i>

25:46.376 --> 25:48.917
Mayakovsky had a Renault,
and we raced around Moscow

25:49.001 --> 25:51.667
at 40 miles an hour with our windows down,

25:51.751 --> 25:53.042
shouting, singing,

25:53.126 --> 25:54.826
and mooning.

25:55.209 --> 25:58.084
He had a nice arse.
My arse was way too fat.

25:58.167 --> 26:00.959
He got his car impounded for moral turpitude.

26:01.042 --> 26:02.376
Mayakovsky, that is, not his car.

26:02.459 --> 26:03.584
His car was innocent.

26:03.834 --> 26:06.709
Is this car, with Death in the driver's seat,

26:06.792 --> 26:07.834
completely innocent?

26:08.001 --> 26:09.501
No fat on his backside.

26:09.626 --> 26:13.001
In 1927, Mary Pickford and Douglas Fairbanks

26:13.126 --> 26:15.417
of Universal Pictures,
Charlie Chaplin's company,

26:15.501 --> 26:18.251
<i>saw Potemkin and invited me
to come to Hollywood</i>

26:18.334 --> 26:20.209
to make a film! Hooray! Hooray! Hooray!

26:21.584 --> 26:24.417
I met them all. All those Hollywood guys.

26:24.501 --> 26:26.209
They all came to Moscow.
Would you believe it?

26:26.417 --> 26:28.167
<i>Joseph Schenck lost in Russia,</i>

26:28.292 --> 26:30.376
but he looked like a Russian smoothie.

26:30.501 --> 26:31.792
All Jews look lost in Russia,

26:31.876 --> 26:33.626
but there is never a better home for them.

26:33.709 --> 26:36.709
He fast-smoked big cigars.
He was a caricature.

26:36.834 --> 26:38.626
It was to make sure no one took him seriously

26:38.709 --> 26:41.042
so he could take everyone else seriously
when they weren't looking.

26:41.459 --> 26:44.126
I am a caricature. I don't smoke fast,

26:44.209 --> 26:45.709
but I can talk fast, don't you think?

26:45.792 --> 26:48.417
Joseph Schenck came
with a Hollywood contract

26:48.501 --> 26:51.251
in his pocket, which was soon in my pocket.

26:51.376 --> 26:55.126
And then my pockets were filled
with Hollywood happiness.

26:55.709 --> 26:57.792
<i>Felicidad Hollywoodus.</i>

27:03.917 --> 27:06.501
To get to Hollywood,
you must first pass through Europe,

27:06.584 --> 27:08.709
and then you have to pass through America

27:08.792 --> 27:12.376
because Hollywood is a separate country
all on its very own.

27:12.792 --> 27:14.626
So like bug-eyed cultural tourists,

27:14.709 --> 27:18.792
we went through Europe,
looking, seeing, shaking hands.

27:18.876 --> 27:20.876
Although it was more like
shaking hands and looking.

27:20.959 --> 27:24.042
I had eyes in my hands,
and they never stopped shaking.

27:24.126 --> 27:29.084
We met George Grosz and Man Ray
and Dos Passes.

27:29.167 --> 27:30.751
Oh, Käthe Kollwitz.

27:30.834 --> 27:32.667
She had at least half a way
for social conscience,

27:32.751 --> 27:34.876
